        <h3>Understanding JPEG quality percentage</h3>
        <p>
          After rendering the page at a given DPI, the image is compressed as JPEG. The
          quality percentage controls how much compression is applied:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>95-100%:</strong> Nearly lossless. Large files but perfect for detailed documents</li>
          <li><strong>85-90%:</strong> Sweet spot for most uses. Invisible quality loss, 40-60% smaller than 100%</li>
          <li><strong>70-80%:</strong> Good for web thumbnails. Some softness visible on text at zoom</li>
          <li><strong>Below 70%:</strong> Noticeable artifacts. Only for very low-bandwidth situations</li>
